{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} {{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{Flagicon|Greece}} "Feggari Kalokerino" | image = | caption = | year = 1981 | country = Greece | artist = [[Yiannis Dimitras]] | as = | with = | language = Greek | languages = | composer = Yiannis Dimitras, Yiorgos Niarchos | lyricist = Yiannis Dimitras | conductor = Yiorgos Niarchos | place = 8th | points = 55 | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1981gr from Diggiloo Thrush] | clip = | prev = Autostop | prev_link = Autostop (Anna Vissi and The Epikouri song) | next_year = 1983 | next = Mou Les | next_link = Mou Les }}
"'''Feggari Kalokerino'''" ([[Greek alphabet|Greek script]]: "'''Φεγγάρι καλοκαιρινό'''", [[English language|English]] translation: "Summer Moon") was the [[Greece|Greek]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1981]], performed in [[Greek language|Greek]] by [[Yiannis Dimitras]].
The song was performed seventeenth on the night (following [[Belgium]]'s [[Emly Starr]] with "[[Samson (song)|Samson]]" and preceding [[Cyprus]]' [[Island (band)|Island]] with "[[Monika (song)|Monika]]"). At the close of voting, the song had received 55 points, placing 8th in a field of 20.
The song is a ballad, with Dimitras telling the summer moon about how it makes him feel. He pledges, for example, to build a church "for the crazy children of love". He was accompanied on the piano by actress and pianist Sofia Houndra, who was not credited on-screen.
Greece elected not to enter the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1982|1982 Contest]]. Thus, the song was succeeded as [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest|Greek representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1983|1983 Contest]] by [[Kristi Stassinopoulou]] with [[Mou Les]].
