'''Rouen-Rive-Droite''' is a large [[railway station]] serving the city of [[Rouen]], [[Normandy]], [[France]]. The station is on Rue Verte in the north of the city. Services are mainly [[Inter-city rail|intercity]] but many services are [[TER Haute Normandie|local]]. There are also [[TGV]] from [[Gare du Havre|Le Havre]] to [[Gare de Marseille-Saint-Charles|Marseille-Saint-Charles]] and to [[Gare de Strasbourg|Strasbourg]].

== History ==
The station opened its doors in 1847 when the Rouen–Le Havre section of the [[Paris–Le Havre railway]] opened to service. The line previously had its terminus at [[Gare de Rouen Saint-Sever|Rouen Rive-Gauche]]. With the increase in traffic, the construction of the new station on the North bank of the [[Seine River|River Seine]] started.  The station building was designed in [[Art Nouveau]] style by architect [[Adolphe Dervaux]], with commissioned sculpture by [[Camille Lefèvre]].  The station was inaugurated on 4 July 1928 by French President [[Gaston Doumergue]]. At first named Rue Verte, the station then changed name to Rive-Droite. In 1994 an interchange was built to serve [[Tramway de Rouen|Rouen métro]].

== Services ==
With the high-speed rail network [[TGV]], Rouen is connected to the following stations:
* [[Gare du Havre|Le Havre]] - Rouen-Rive-Droite - [[Gare de Mantes-la-Jolie|Mantes-la-Jolie]] - [[Gare de Versailles-Chantiers|Versailles-Chantiers]] - [[Gare de Massy TGV|Massy]] - [[Gare de Lyon-Part-Dieu|Lyon-Part-Dieu]] - [[Gare de Valence TGV|Valence TGV]] - [[Gare d'Avignon TGV|Avignon TGV]] - [[Gare de Marseille-Saint-Charles|Marseille-Saint-Charles]]

