{{short description|An old and stable part of the continental lithosphere, that occupies large portions of South Africa, Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe}} [[File:Cratons West Gondwana.svg|thumb|right|Approximate location of [[Mesoproterozoic]] (older than 1.3&nbsp;Ga) cratons in South America and Africa.]] The '''Kalahari Craton''' is a [[craton]], an old and stable part of the [[continental lithosphere]], that occupies large portions of [[South Africa]], [[Botswana]], [[Namibia]] and [[Zimbabwe]]. It consists of two cratons separated by the [[Limpopo Belt]]: the larger [[Kaapvaal Craton]] to the south and the smaller [[Zimbabwe Craton]] to the north. The [[Namaqua Belt]] is the southern margin of the Kaapvaal Craton.<ref name="Zeh-etal">{{Harvnb|Zeh|Gerdes|Barton Jr|2009|loc=Kalahari Craton, pp. 934–935}}</ref>
Parts of the Kalahari Craton are now located in East (the [[Grunehogna Craton]]) and West Antarctica ([[Haag Nunataks]]) and the Falkland Islands.<ref name="Jac-etal">{{Harvnb|Jacobs|Pisarevsky|Thomas|Becker|2008|loc=Abstract}}</ref> The name was first introduced by {{Harvnb|Clifford|1970}}.<ref name="Jac-intro">{{Harvnb|Jacobs|Pisarevsky|Thomas|Becker|2008|loc=Introduction, pp. 2–3}}</ref>
== Formation == Following a terminology introduced in 2008,<ref name="Jac-intro" /> the Archaean-Palaeoproterozoic core of the craton is called the Proto-Kalahari Craton. This core plus [[Accretion (geology)|accreted]] Mesoproterozoic crust and dispersed non-African fragments compose the Kalahari Craton. Before the [[Pan-African Orogeny]], the Kalahari Craton was much larger than it is today, but its [[Suture (geology)|sutures]] and therefore its extent are difficult to locate due to later [[Overprinting (geology)|overprinting]].<ref name="Jac-intro" />
The Kaapvaal Craton, Zimbabwe Craton, and Limpopo Belt are made of Archaean [[terrane]]s and contain crust at least 3.2&nbsp;{{Abbr|Ga|billion year old}} and are underlain by a thick ({{Convert|250|km|abbr=on}}) layer of buoyant mantle that is producing garnets and diamonds.<ref name="Zeh-etal" />
During the Palaeoproterozoic the northwest margin of the Archaean core grew by accretion and had formed a Proto-Kalahari Craton by 1.75&nbsp;Ga. During the period 1.4–1.0&nbsp;Ga subduction occurred along the northwest margin followed by continental collisions along the eastern and southern margins. By this time enough Mesoproterozoic crust had accreted to transform the Kalahari Craton. At 1.11&nbsp;Ga, during the assembly of the supercontinent [[Rodinia]], the Kalahari Craton was affected by the [[Umkondo-Borg Large Igneous Province]].<ref name="Jac-etal" /> At {{Circa}} 1.15–.98&nbsp;Ga the Kalahari Craton collided with the eastern margin of [[Laurentia]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Dalziel|Mosher|Gahagan|2000|loc=Abstract}}</ref>
